fields.bio: Professor Jamie Evans provided Marita with the initial inspiration for founding Robogals while he was Head of Electrical Engineering at the University of Melbourne.  He continues to be a great mentor for the team, despite his unfortunate defection to Monash University.

fields.infobox:
With members all over the world, our job is to nurture our chapters across the world to achieve their full potential, as well as expand to even more universities!

Our primary activities are:
  • Mentoring the Robogals Regional Executive Officers, who in turn, coordinate the Regional Teams and chapters in their region.
  • Constantly working to improve the training given to new chapter executive committee members, and running our annual SINE (Seminars Inducting New Exec) conferences.
  • Liaising with universities to set up new Robogals chapters.
  • General organisational development and improvement - e.g. seeking expert advice on teaching methods.
  • Maintaining all of Robogals' IT infrastructure globally, including myRobogals, websites and email.

We love receiving helpful feedback and suggestions from the Robogals members on the ground - just email our team on support@robogals.org and we'll get back to you as soon as we can!

fields.infobox:
Robogals Rural and Regional Ambassadors Program involves engineering students from rural universities all across Australia. Different from Chapter school visits, the RRR Ambassadors visit rural schools around their rural university and near their home town and give talks to girls about engineering.

The 2014 Ambassadors include:

From Queensland-

Sophia Marmara, James Cook University
Manveet Kaur, James Cook University
Michelle Makubalo, James Cook University

From Victoria-

Rebecca Littler, La Trobe University
Christie White, La Trobe University

If you want to get in contact with any of these people email munxin@robogals.org

fields.award_description: Awarded to the Robogals chapter to have had the biggest impact on increasing girls' interest in engineering. This is a deliberately broad definition, so that all activities run by a Robogals chapter are counted!

Awarded to the chapter that teaches the most number of girls through robotics workshops organised primarily by the Robogals chapter, either by visiting the school or having the school visit your uni. This particular award is for robotics workshops only and does not include girls impacted in other ways.

Girls count as 1 the first time they participate in a robotics workshop, and 0.5 for every subsequent visit.  This is an attempt to strike a good balance between rewarding breadth and rewarding depth.  Boys attending robotics workshops are not counted towards this award.

Awarded to the chapter that has the most vibrant Robogals community on campus, as determined by the number of members, social events, and camaraderie amongst members and particularly amongst the executive committee.
Awarded to the chapter that communicated the most clearly, effectively and frequently.
Awarded to the chapter that demonstrated the most initiative or creativity in robotics workshops, events, recruitment strategies or any other area.
This is perhaps a strange name for an award, but since one of our Robogals values is "integrity", defined as "being your word", we have an award for it.

Awarded to the chapter that runs the best event during the year. Criteria include the number of attendees (particularly the number of schoolgirls), how well-organised the event was, and how effective it was at increasing girls' interest in engineering.
Awarded for the best publicity received in the media or other forums. Criteria include the reach of the publicity, and how well Robogals was portrayed.
Awarded to the most creative chapter. This award is no longer awarded; it has been somewhat superseded by Most Initiative.
Awarded to the chapter that demonstrated the best teamwork throughout the year. This award is no longer awarded; it has been superseded by Best Community.
For the chapter that had the most Facebook fans. This award is no longer awarded.
For those chapters that were awesome but didn't quite make Biggest Impact :)
Awarded to the chapter that ran the best rural & regional road trip

fields.description: for their Robogals Science and Engineering Expo

- 20 trained volunteers (not including exec and Global)
- 175 members on myRobogals
- Sent 40 emails to all of these members during the year
Taught 279 girls in the period 10/09/2010 to 24/09/2011 according to the above method of counting.  The next best chapter was 144!  These guys blitzed it!
For their robotics workshops at the London Science Museum
For teaching robotics workshops to 214.5 girls in the period Feb 2011 to Feb 2012 (weighted girl-visits: 1 for first visit and 0.5 for repeat visit)
For constantly tracking against their goals throughout the year, and keeping up with and exceeding them!
For having many, many on-campus events throughout the year to engage students including BBQs, information sessions and social events.  Have 34 active volunteers.
For their booth at the Grand Prix expo - reached a lot of people and resulted in many inquiries from schools, who then had Robogals conduct robotics workshops at their school.
For reaching 1,088 girls in the period Sep 2011 to Sep 2012 using the above method of counting.

This was very close and difficult to choose as the standard this year was so high!  The board awarded this to ANU because of their broad impact in many areas.  This chapter did everything a Robogals chapter should do: taught lots of robotics workshops (smashed their goal by over 150%, reaching 410 girls, and a few hundred boys too); ran two rural trips; recruited, trained and used lots of volunteers, thus engaging with their university community; held 8 events including BBQs and NXT drop-ins; partnered with Codarra Robotics Challenge; raised funds to buy LEGO NXTs and laptops; held regular team meetings with 92% attendance. They are also feedback junkies who like to analyse everything they're doing to ensure that it's actually having an impact.  What a great effort from this chapter in only their first year - they have had a large on-the-ground impact in schools as well as creating a solid Robogals community that will ensure an ever-bigger impact in the years to come!

Biggest Impact was difficult to choose this year as the standard was so high!  Melbourne won an Honourable Mention for being a very active chapter that reached over 1,000 girls all across Victoria, including five rural trips!

Robogals Melbourne had a solid year Sept 2012-Sept 2013; exceeding all goals they set for themselves.  They constantly achieved successful results in all areas of their chapter; from events like attendance to the Avalon International Air Show to gaining more active volunteers to teaching 1392 girls.

Robogals Melbourne has established a professional system of communicating with their members.  They created a monthly newsletter that is distributed, they have an active Facebook group, good system from finding volunteers for workshops and also establishing and maintaining good contacts with industry.

Robogals Canberra: our local television stars!  Appearing on Prime Possum Kids Television show.  Introducing young girls to engineering on prime-time tv!  Their appearance can be found on Yahoo 7 website: "Dust and Rust: Part 2".
For their work collaborating with Disney on the Tinkerbell Movie and going to the Pasadena Education Expo to increase their reach in their the community.
For the creation of many documents, ideas, stickers, activity booklets, library visits and activity sheets.
For persistence in the face of difficulty, and working through and sticking to what they had planned with minimal volunteers and executive members.
Curriculum and Lesson Sharing: This forum focuses on discussions regarding session ideas, reviews of lessons, new topics, new ways of teaching and a place to share our lesson plans with each other!
